Abstract: The importance of information technology, as a mechanism for creating and sustaining competitive advantage, is a concept understood by many private and public sector organisations. The continuous investment in IT, in both sectors, and the gradual alignment of global business and information systems thinking has reduced the utility of traditional models of strategy. This paper advocates the Soft Systems view for the purpose of formulating information systems strategy; derived from end-users and other stakeholders participatively using Future Workshops. The history of the Scan-dinavian approach in development is fast becoming an accepted approach: this paper attempts to convey this message of participative democracy in the context of strategic information systems planning. 
