Reference-contexts: Future Workshops were originally devised for citizen groups with limited resources who wanted to contribute towards the decision making process of public planning authorities <ref> (Jungk & Mullert, 1987) </ref>. More recently, they have been utilised by Kensing & Madsen (1991) as a technique for the participatory design of information systems. Future Workshops enable users to focus directly on the problems and concepts that govern their tasks. <p> A future workshop is divided into three phases: Critique phase: designed to draw out issues about current work practice and thinking. Speaking time is restricted to thirty seconds to allow all participants to express themselves <ref> (Jungk & Mullert, 1987) </ref>. Fantasy phase: allows participants the freedom to use their imagination on issues they feel are of significance. No extremes are specified in order to allow free thought. Implementation phase: participants rationalise their ideas into the real world and reason about the resources that would be required.
